Cape Town - DA leader Mmusi Maimane was stopped from delivering a memorandum on crime at the Nyanga police by Deputy Police Minister Bongani Mkongi.
 

 The memorandum was part of the DA's #SendTheArmyNow march, which seeks to deploy the army in crime hotspots on the Cape Flats. 
 Maimane led hundreds of Cape Town residents participating in the march against crime to the Nyanga police station.

 
  
 
 
  A tense stand-off ensued after Mkongi wanted to address supporters of the DA, outside the police station. He said the DA was spreading lies about the police which he wanted to defend.
 
 
  
 
 
  “You are dividing our people. This rubbish of the DA must stop. I am not accepting this,” Mkongi told Western Cape Community Safety MEC Dan Plato.
 
 
  
 
 
  “Look here, on the one side you have coloured people and on the other side are blacks. This is wrong. We deploying more police to the Cape Flats, we have tactical units assisting the local police and doing everything possible. Why do they want to politicise it,” he asked.
 
 
  
 
 
  
   







